Vheadline
p2
VPaying tribute to Deekshitar
p3
sVnews
p4
VMuthuswami Deekshitar is one among the music trinity, the others being Thyagaraja and Shyama Sastry, contemporaries and all hailing from the same place.In connection with his 173rd death anniversary, Nada Prabha Trust, launched by a vainika of the contemporary scene, Ayyagari Shyama Sundar, former Principal of the Government College of Music and Dance, Vijayawada, organised a Carnatic music show. The show was held at Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan last week.V. Hema, Jayaram Kuruganti, Varanasi Sri Sowmya, Kartika Anagha and Kalyana Vasant were some of the younger lot. They gave vocal concerts, singing compositions of Deekshitar. Later, highly experienced and senior veena playing sister duo, Bandi Shyamala and Subbalakshmi, choseSri Gananathimm Bhajarein Eesamanohari ragam andSrikamalambikein Kalyani. Violinists Pavan Singh and O. Rajsekhar and mridangam players K. Shyamkumar and Sridharacharya played supporting roles for different concerts.The major showpiece of the festival was a vocal concert by Hyderabad sisters Lalitha and Haripriya.Their repertoire was packed with interesting numbers of Deekshitar.Lalitambikamin Devakriya,Akhilandeswari Rakshamamin Dwijavanti andParandhamavatiin Dharmavati were the numbers that figured in the earlier part of their concert.The Dharmavati piece was notable for raga essay andswarakalpana. Bhairavi forBalagopalamwas also delineated and the kriti part was marked by an engagingswarakalpana.Mayetvam Yahiin Tharangini andAbhayambikayaiin Kedaragowla were other numbers notable for their expression. Dwaram Durga Prasada Rao on the violin and D.S.R. Murthy on the mridangam, both seasoned artistes, accompanied them.
